                    <note type="abstract" xml:id="abstract-en-370">
                        <quote source="#bib370-1">Monk and abbot.</quote>
                    </note>
                    <note type="description">In hagiography: Barṣawmā was the head of mourners at a monastery near Melitene. He was a disciple of <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/1109">Abraham of the high mountain</persName>. He was a rigid monk who chased the Jews out of Jerusalem. He was a friend of Dioscorus of Alexandria, leader at the Robber Council of 449. He mobilized his monks to rehabilitate Eutyches. He condemned the priest Flavian at the Council of Chalcedon and was expelled at the Council of Chalcedon.</note>
                    <sex value="M" source="#bib370-7">male</sex>
                    <death>
                        <date when="0458" syriaca-computed-start="0458-01-01" source="#bib370-7">0458</date>
                        <date notBefore="0443" notAfter="0473" syriaca-computed-end="0473-01-01" syriaca-computed-start="0443-01-01" source="#bib370-1">ca. 458</date>
                    </death>
                    <note>Fiey provides the following bibliographic citations: <quote source="#bib370-7">Voir Ia Vie de Barsaum, avec ses 99 ou 100 miracles, ecrite vers 55Q--61, dans
Nau, "Resume" (1913, 1914). Version ethiopienne: S. Grebaut, ROC 13 (1908),
et 14 (1909) .
DHGE, s.v. Barsauma 1, VI, col. 946- 47 (G. Bardy).
BS, II, 842 (J .-M. Sauget).
V. surtout : Honigmann, Bar$aumii, 6- 23 ; H. Kaufhold, dans Hugoye 3 (2000).</quote>
                    </note>
